  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Title III of the USA PATRIOT Act\n- International Money Laundering Abatement and Anti-Terrorism Financing Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (engaging in monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. State Level:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\n4. Key Elements Typically Addressed:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained money\n- Conducting financial transactions with proceeds from criminal activity\n- Reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Penalties including fines and imprisonment\n\nThese statutes generally aim to:\n- Detect and prevent financial crimes\n- Trace criminal proceeds\n- Impose reporting requirements on financial institutions\n- Establish criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\nThe laws cover a wide range of financial transactions and apply to various types of criminal enterprises.",
